An auction at Phillips offers a rare collection of William Eggleston prints=
,
made with an arcane and all-but-extinct process to amp up the vividness of =
everyday life.

Marion Maneker ( https://puck.news/author/marion-maneker/?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Marion Maneker ( https://puck.news/author/marion-maneker/?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Guy Stricherz and Irene Malli are retiring. They=E2=80=99ve had a
great run. In 1981, Guy started the Color Vision Imaging Laboratory, in wha=
t we now call Nolita, but which was then just Little Italy, to make dye tra=
nsfer prints of color photographs. An offshoot of the Technicolor film proc=
ess that revolutionized the movie industry, dye transfer printing was inven=
ted in 1946; the process dominated the advertising industry and graphic art=
s for nearly half a century, until 1994, when Kodak discontinued making the=
 materials for the process and sold its remaining
stock of film, paper, and dyes to master printers like Stricherz.

For the past 30 years, Stricherz has been making color dye transfer prints =
along with Malli, who, after graduating from Cooper Union, answered an ad f=
or a job at the studio that Stricherz ran with another partner. She eventua=
lly married the master printer=E2=80=94and became one herself. They=E2=80=
=99ve done this for many photographers, but none more than William Egglesto=
n, of whose work they have made editions of some 250
images in dye transfer. =E2=80=9CEvery print is kind of like a puzzle,=E2=
=80=9D Malli said. =E2=80=9CYou have to figure out how to get from what you=
 want to the final print.=E2=80=9D Regarding what makes the process so spec=
ial, Stricherz has said ( https://www.phillips.com/article/155494003/color-=
vision-master-prints-from-guy-stricherz-and-irene-malli?utm_campaign=3DWall=
+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBE=
RS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm=
_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ): =E2=80=9CThe dyes commingle and sort of dance=
 to produce a bond that gives the print an almost three-dimensional
look.=E2=80=9D

The combination of Stricherz, Malli, and Eggleston has become a thing in it=
s own right lately. David Zwirner gallery just closed a show in Los Angeles=
 titled William Eggleston, The Last Dyes, featuring some of Eggleston=E2=80=
=99s images using the very last of the Kodak dye transfer materials=E2=80=
=94some stockpiled by the Stricherzes, some from Eggleston=E2=80=99s own dw=
indled supply. This week, Phillips opens an exhibition of 43 lots of Eggles=
ton=E2=80=99s work, signed by the photographer, for an
auction ( https://www.phillips.com/auction/NY040525?utm_campaign=3DWall+Pow=
er+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%=
283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_ter=
m=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) on March 18. These dye transfer prints are Striche=
rz and Malli=E2=80=99s own printer=E2=80=99s proofs=E2=80=94the apex of the=
 artist=E2=80=99s intent in the hierarchy of fidelity and expression, and t=
he reference point by which all other examples can be measured.

William Eggleston,=C2=A0Untitled (Peaches!) (1973).

Making dye transfer prints is a persnickety process that=E2=80=99s precise =
in the way it generates
color; it requires both the experience of a master and the approval of the =
artist. When working with Eggleston, the Stricherzes would create as many p=
rints in the numbered edition as commissioned, along with a set number of a=
rtist=E2=80=99s proofs. They would also, by predetermined agreement, make a=
 single printer=E2=80=99s proof that Eggleston would sign. Because of the p=
rocess=E2=80=99s precision, and since the dyes do not fade in the way other=
 printing processes do, these dye transfer prints are the perfected master
prints of Eggleston=E2=80=99s work. Or, as Phillips head of photography Van=
essa Hallett said: =E2=80=9CYou can=E2=80=99t have a better print than thei=
r printer=E2=80=99s proof.=E2=80=9D

Remember Los Alamos
-------------------

Among the lots in the auction is a rare
portfolio ( https://www.phillips.com/detail/william-eggleston/215079?utm_ca=
mpaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Powe=
r+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcu=
stomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) of 75 dye transfer prints titled =
Los Alamos, which captures the best of Eggleston=E2=80=99s images from 1965=
-74. Los Alamos was made in an edition of seven, Hallett told me, and of th=
ose seven, two are in museums (MoMA and Museum Ludwig in Germany), three ar=
e owned by well-known collectors with commitments to institutions, and one =
set was broken up.
(Translation: It=E2=80=99s unlikely that you=E2=80=99ll ever get another ch=
ance to buy one.)

If that were not enough to emphasize its rarity, the portfolio is being sol=
d as a single lot with two other portfolios of 13 photographs each, Cousins=
 and Lost and Found, that come from negatives that Eggleston thought were l=
ost at the time he created Los Alamos. Together, the entire lot contains 10=
1 of Eggleston=E2=80=99s most famous and consequential images printed by dy=
e transfer, and it=E2=80=99s
what the photographer wanted to be seen as a single body of work. Its $2 mi=
llion estimate would be a record for Eggleston=E2=80=99s work at auction. L=
os Alamos (just the 75 prints) hit a then-record of just over $1 million at=
 auction in October 2008, a terrible time for the art market; that record l=
asted 16 years until last November, when an oversize print (not a dye trans=
fer) nearly 5 feet tall, of a cocktail on a plane, sold at auction for the =
current record of $1.4 million.

William Eggleston, Memphis (Tricycle) (1969).

In addition, the sale contains the largest dye transfer prints of Eggleston=
=E2=80=99s seven most famous
images, what he calls his =E2=80=9Cmagnificent seven.=E2=80=9D If you follo=
w contemporary art at all, you=E2=80=99ll likely recognize Untitled (Peache=
s!), Memphis (Tricycle), or Greenwood, Mississippi (Red Ceiling) immediatel=
y. These examples are still not very large, at 17 by 26 inches. (Eggleston =
had much larger prints of these images made in 2012=E2=80=945 feet tall or =
wide, depending on the orientation of the photograph=E2=80=94but those are =
made with the pigment print process on board, instead
of photographic paper.)

Mysteriously, though, this is the first time anyone outside the Eggleston o=
rbit has seen prints in this size of the images. The cataloging says the wo=
rks are from an edition of 10, plus three lettered artist=E2=80=99s proofs =
printed in 2015. Not only have these prints never been auctioned before=E2=
=80=94but until the Stricherzes decided to sell some of their printer=E2=80=
=99s proofs, Hallett had not known of their existence.

The Eggleston Mystique
----------------------

Phillips has an interesting position in the photography market. =E2=80=9CTh=
e majority of collectors I
work with,=E2=80=9D Hallett said, =E2=80=9Care contemporary collectors who =
incorporate photographs into their collection.=E2=80=9D Like Cindy Sherman,=
 Andreas Gursky, and Bernd and Hilla Becher, Eggleston appeals to collector=
s who view his work as a new way of seeing, one that just happens to use th=
e medium of photography.

His reputation as a photographer and artist is also bound up with the impac=
t and acceptance of color photography as a
medium. In 1976, MoMA gave Eggleston a watershed show that changed the way =
the medium was viewed by artists, photographers, and collectors. After the =
MoMA show, photographers shed their reliance on using moody black-and-white=
 printing to achieve the seriousness of high art. After all, MoMA had valid=
ated color.

Eggleston=E2=80=99s discovery of the dye transfer printing process in 1972 =
was integral to his success. Stricherz and Malli did not become Eggleston=
=E2=80=99s go-to dye transfer printers until
later, but once the trio met, their work became intertwined, because the ma=
rried duo could realize the photographer=E2=80=99s vision in ways that othe=
r printers could not.

After all, in color photography, making an image is really only half of the=
 process. The rest is all about making the print. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s wel=
l enough to make an excellent transparency in the studio or out in the fiel=
d,=E2=80=9D Stricherz said in a video ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DT=
DEogEt_NeQ&utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_co=
ntent=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_actio=
n&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) made for the Zwi=
rner exhibition. =E2=80=9CBut you want a print, and that is the thing.=E2=
=80=9D Artists don=E2=80=99t exhibit transparencies, which we used to call =
slides; a carousel slide projector is an awkward way to view an artist=E2=
=80=99s work. =E2=80=9CYou need a physical object,=E2=80=9D Stricherz said.

And it=E2=80=99s a lost art. The dye transfer process was already fading in=
 commercial relevance when Stricherz first got involved in the early 1980s.=
 =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s kind of nice to be in a medium that is really=E2=80=
=94it=E2=80=99s not
practiced anymore,=E2=80=9D Stricherz said ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?=
v=3DTDEogEt_NeQ&utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&u=
tm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_=
action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ). =E2=80=9CT=
here=E2=80=99s something about it being so rarefied =E2=80=A6 to do somethi=
ng that nobody else is doing.=E2=80=9D Now, with the last of the Kodak mate=
rials used up, and the knowledge that Stricherz and Malli acquired over dec=
ades all but useless, it=E2=80=99s pretty much gone.

The secret of the dye transfer process was in the color separation. Though =
it frustrated many others,
Stricherz had the control to make it extremely flexible, and produce a stri=
kingly different print from one hour to the next. Imagine the joy that Eggl=
eston must have felt to work alongside him tweaking the colors, tones, and =
highlights. =E2=80=9CYou can radically change the print,=E2=80=9D Stricherz=
 said. =E2=80=9CWhat you=E2=80=99re trying to do is make a print that looks=
 as close to that transparency as can be done. And that=E2=80=99s really wh=
at William Eggleston wants. He wants a faithful reproduction of the transpa=
rency at full
frame.=E2=80=9D

