50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;"><st=
rong>Guy Stricherz</strong> and <strong>Irene Malli</strong> are retiring. =
They=E2=80=99ve had a
great run. In 1981, Guy started the Color Vision Imaging Laboratory, in wha=
t we now call Nolita, but which was then just Little Italy, to make dye tra=
nsfer prints of color photographs. An offshoot of the Technicolor film proc=
ess that revolutionized the movie industry, dye transfer printing was inven=
ted in 1946; the process dominated the advertising industry and graphic art=
s for nearly half a century, until 1994, when Kodak discontinued making the=
 materials for the process and sold its remaining
stock of film, paper, and dyes to master printers like Stricherz.<br/><br/>=
For the past 30 years, Stricherz has been making color dye transfer prints =
along with Malli, who, after graduating from Cooper Union, answered an ad f=
or a job at the studio that Stricherz ran with another partner. She eventua=
lly married the master printer=E2=80=94and became one herself. They=E2=80=
=99ve done this for many photographers, but none more than <strong>William =
Eggleston</strong>, of whose work they have made editions of some 250
images in dye transfer. =E2=80=9CEvery print is kind of like a puzzle,=E2=
=80=9D Malli said. =E2=80=9CYou have to figure out how to get from what you=
 want to the final print.=E2=80=9D Regarding what makes the process so spec=
ial, Stricherz <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnV=
DJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dWaHlzV0RLenRkd1RrcmRlZC00dz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cucGhpbGxpcHMuY29tL2FydGljbGUvMTU1NDk0MDAzL2NvbG9yLXZpc2lvbi1tYXN0ZXItcHJ=
pbnRzLWZyb20tZ3V5LXN0cmljaGVyei1hbmQtaXJlbmUtbWFsbGk_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPVdhbG=
wrUG93ZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgzJTJGMTElMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50P=
VdhbGwrUG93ZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgzJTJGMTElMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRp=
dW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJ=
tPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibG=
lua19pZCI6MjExNjM2NH0/7814b1aa4d67aa714354e6457a028e56195b76fdf0f2b0d9ef2a6=
9ae7f8f3f0a" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">has said</a=
>: =E2=80=9CThe dyes commingle and sort of dance to produce a bond that giv=
es the print an almost three-dimensional
look.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>The combination of Stricherz, Malli, and Eggleston =
has become a thing in its own right lately. David Zwirner gallery just clos=
ed a show in Los Angeles titled <em>William Eggleston, The Last Dyes</em>, =
featuring some of Eggleston=E2=80=99s images using the very last of the Kod=
ak dye transfer materials=E2=80=94some stockpiled by the Stricherzes, some =
from Eggleston=E2=80=99s own dwindled supply. This week, Phillips opens an =
exhibition of 43 lots of Eggleston=E2=80=99s work, signed by the photograph=
er, for an
