50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;">Phi=
llips has an interesting position in the photography market. =E2=80=9CThe m=
ajority of collectors I
work with,=E2=80=9D Hallett said, =E2=80=9Care contemporary collectors who =
incorporate photographs into their collection.=E2=80=9D Like<strong> Cindy =
Sherman</strong>, <strong>Andreas Gursky</strong>, and <strong>Bernd</stron=
g> and <strong>Hilla Becher</strong>, Eggleston appeals to collectors who v=
iew his work as a new way of seeing, one that just happens to use the mediu=
m of photography.<br/><br/>His reputation as a photographer and artist is a=
lso bound up with the impact and acceptance of color photography as a
medium. In 1976, MoMA gave Eggleston a watershed show that changed the way =
the medium was viewed by artists, photographers, and collectors. After the =
MoMA show, photographers shed their reliance on using moody black-and-white=
 printing to achieve the seriousness of high art. After all, MoMA had valid=
ated color.<br/><br/>Eggleston=E2=80=99s discovery of the dye transfer prin=
ting process in 1972 was integral to his success. Stricherz and Malli did n=
ot become Eggleston=E2=80=99s go-to dye transfer printers until
later, but once the trio met, their work became intertwined, because the ma=
rried duo could realize the photographer=E2=80=99s vision in ways that othe=
r printers could not.<br/><br/>After all, in color photography, making an i=
mage is really only half of the process. The rest is all about making the p=
rint. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s well enough to make an excellent transparency i=
n the studio or out in the field,=E2=80=9D Stricherz said in a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dWaHlz=
V0RLenRkd1RrcmRlZC00dz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g=
_dj1UREVvZ0V0X05lUVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1XYWxsK1Bvd2VyKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUl=
MrJTI4MyUyRjExJTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1XYWxsK1Bvd2VyKy0rU1VCU0NSS=
UJFUlMrJTI4MyUyRjExJTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAy=
NnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmE=
iLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjIxMTYzNjd9/aa456=
79dd4b7927654348dc0428b9a49eca0fc92ac2bd55f9c89d26d7058b756" style=3D"text-=
decoration:underline;color:
#d40000;">video</a> made for the Zwirner exhibition. =E2=80=9CBut you want =
a print, and that is the thing.=E2=80=9D Artists don=E2=80=99t exhibit tran=
sparencies, which we used to call slides; a carousel slide projector is an =
awkward way to view an artist=E2=80=99s work. =E2=80=9CYou need a physical =
object,=E2=80=9D Stricherz said.<br/><br/>And it=E2=80=99s a lost art. The =
dye transfer process was already fading in commercial relevance when Strich=
erz first got involved in the early 1980s. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s kind of ni=
ce to be in a medium that is really=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s not
practiced anymore,=E2=80=9D Stricherz <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/=
c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dWaHlzV0RLenRkd1RrcmRlZC00dz0iL=
CJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dj1UREVvZ0V0X05lUVx1MDAy=
NnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1XYWxsK1Bvd2VyKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MyUyRjExJTJGMjUlMjl=
cdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1XYWxsK1Bvd2VyKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MyUyRjExJTJGMj=
UlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZ=
XIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYw=
NjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjIxMTYzNjd9/aa45679dd4b7927654348dc0428b9a=
49eca0fc92ac2bd55f9c89d26d7058b756" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;colo=
r:#d40000;">said</a>. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s something about it being so =
rarefied =E2=80=A6 to do something that nobody else is doing.=E2=80=9D Now,=
 with the last of the Kodak materials used up, and the knowledge that Stric=
herz and Malli acquired over decades all but useless, it=E2=80=99s pretty m=
uch gone.<br/><br/>The secret of the dye transfer process was in the color =
separation. Though it frustrated many others,
Stricherz had the control to make it extremely flexible, and produce a stri=
kingly different print from one hour to the next. Imagine the joy that Eggl=
eston must have felt to work alongside him tweaking the colors, tones, and =
highlights. =E2=80=9CYou can radically change the print,=E2=80=9D Stricherz=
 said. =E2=80=9CWhat you=E2=80=99re trying to do is make a print that looks=
 as close to that transparency as can be done. And that=E2=80=99s really wh=
at William Eggleston wants. He wants a faithful reproduction of the transpa=
rency at full
frame.=E2=80=9D</p></div>
